<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-17T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-17T12:00:00-05:00" n="787" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d787">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/12158:
                                    Telegram</note>
                                <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi>
                                        (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-17T19:00:00+02:00">June 17, 1941—7
                                            p.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 17—12:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>2500. My 2499, June 17, 6 p.m.,<note n="8" xml:id="d787fn8">Not
                                        printed.</note> and Beirut’s 198, June 8. I have
                                    communicated the substance of Beirut’s telegram orally to the
                                    Foreign Office and when I saw Mr, Eden last evening he asked me
                                    to say how very much the;British Government appreciates the
                                    attitude and help of Mr. Engert.</p>
                                <closer>
                                    <signed>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                                    </signed>
                                </closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>